Supplementary analysis: a comparison between the subsampling approach and Gaussian random fields (GRFs) approach in simulating random Desikan data with spatial autocorrelation as measured by Global Moranâ€™s I

0. Setup

code_path='F:/Google Drive/post-doc/vitural_histology_revisit/new_code' # path to the code

1. Load functions

library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)
library(ggplot2)
library(grid)
library(gridExtra)
library(dplyr)
source(file.path(code_path,'spatial_functions.R'))

2. Global Moranâ€™s I for randomly stimulated brain maps

Figure S1. Global Moranâ€™s Is for randomly stimulated brain maps. The histogram shows the distributions of the Global Moranâ€™s I values for 1000 random brain maps, which were simulated by drawing each regional value independently from a uniform distribution ranging from -1 to 1. The subplots display the results of nine simulations conducted at different random states. The vertical line indicates the mean values of the distribution. The average Moranâ€™s I for the randomly generated brain maps was centered around -0.03, which is the expected value for no spatial autocorrelation (i.e., -1/(34-1)=-0.03). This result suggests that the Moranâ€™s I is an effective indicator of spatial dependence among the regions of Desikan atlas.

plist=list()
for (seed in c(2022:2030)) {
  set.seed(seed)
  df = matrix(runif(34 * 1000, min = -1, max = 1), nrow = 34)
  colnames(df)=paste0('null_',c(1:1000))
  df.moran = get_column_moran_idx(df)
  hist_data = hist(df.moran$moran_idx, breaks = 50, plot = FALSE)
  mu = mean(df.moran$moran_idx) # calculate the mean
  s_d=sd(df.moran$moran_idx)
  p=ggplot(data = df.moran, aes(x = moran_idx)) +
    geom_histogram(bins = 50, fill = "grey") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = mu, color = "red", linewidth = 1) +
    annotate("text", x = mu+0.005, y = 85, 
             label = paste("Mean:", round(mu, 4)), 
             color = "red", hjust = 0) +
    annotate("text", x = mu+0.005, y = 85 * 0.90, 
             label = paste("Sd:", round(s_d, 4)), 
             color = "red", hjust = 0)+
    ggtitle(sprintf("Random brain map (seed = %s)", seed)) +
    xlab("Global Moran's I") +
    ylab('Count')+
    ylim(c(0,90))+
    theme_minimal()
  plist[[as.character(seed)]] = p
}
grid.arrange(grobs=plist)

3. Global Moranâ€™s I for brain maps that were simulated using the Gaussian random fields (GRFs) approach.

Figure S2. Global Moranâ€™s I for brain maps that were simulated using the Gaussian random fields (GRFs) approach. More details about this approach and implementation can be found in previous studies (Burt, et al., 2020; Markello and Misic, 2021). Briefly, for each simulated brain map, the two dense, three-dimensional GRFs were created and the level of spatial autocorrelation was determined by the slope of the fieldâ€™s power spectral density (i.e., alpha). Then the generated GRFs were projected onto the fsaverage5 and the Desikan data on the left hemisphere was extracted. The subplots show the results of three simulations with different power spectral density as measured by alpha. The histogram shows the distributions of the Global Moranâ€™s Is for 1000 simulated brain maps. The vertical line indicates the mean values of the distribution.

alphas=c(0.1,0.2,0.3)
plist=list()
for (alpha in alphas) {
  df = read.csv(sprintf('%s/random_brain_maps/alpha%s_lh_simbrain_DK.csv', code_path,alpha),
                 row.names = 1)
  
  df.moran = get_column_moran_idx(df)
  
  hist_data = hist(df.moran$moran_idx, breaks = 50, plot = FALSE)
  mu = mean(df.moran$moran_idx) # calculate the mean
  s_d=sd(df.moran$moran_idx)
  p=ggplot(data = df.moran, aes(x = moran_idx)) +
    geom_histogram(bins = 50, fill = "grey") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = mu, color = "red", linewidth = 1) +
    annotate("text", x = mu+0.005, y = max(hist_data$counts) * 0.95, 
             label = paste("Mean:", round(mu, 4)), 
             color = "red", hjust = 0) +
    annotate("text", x = mu+0.005, y = max(hist_data$counts) * 0.90, 
             label = paste("Sd:", round(s_d, 4)), 
             color = "red", hjust = 0)+
    ggtitle(sprintf("GRF (alpha = %s)", alpha)) +
    xlab("Global Moran's I") +
    ylab('Count')+
    theme_minimal()
  plist[[as.character(alpha)]] = p
  }
grid.arrange(grobs=plist,ncol=3)

4. Global Moranâ€™s Is for brain maps that were simulated using the subsampling approach.

Figure S3. Global Moranâ€™s Is for brain maps that were simulated using the subsampling approach. 1000 random brain maps with spatial autocorrelation were simulated by randomly drawing a subset of 1,000 brain maps with Moranâ€™s I centered at a desired value with a standard deviation of 0.001 from 100,000 random brain maps where each regional value was independently drawn from a uniform distribution ranging from -1 to 1. The subplots show the results of nine simulations with different random states (i.e., 2022, 2023, 2024) and target Moranâ€™s Is (0.01, 0.02, 0.03). The histogram shows the distributions of the Global Moranâ€™s Is for 1000 simulated brain maps. The vertical line indicates the mean values of the distribution.

plist=list()
for (moran2sim in c(0.01,0.02,0.03)){
  for (seed in c(2022, 2023, 2024)){
  df = read.csv(sprintf('F:/Google Drive/post-doc/vitural_histology_revisit/new_code/random_brain_maps/moran_%s_lh_simbrain_DK_seed%s.csv',moran2sim,seed),
                row.names = 1)

  df.moran = get_column_moran_idx(df)
  hist_data = hist(df.moran$moran_idx, breaks = 30, plot = FALSE)
  mu = mean(df.moran$moran_idx) # calculate the mean
  s_d=sd(df.moran$moran_idx)
  p=ggplot(data = df.moran, aes(x = moran_idx)) +
    geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "grey") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = mu, color = "red", linewidth = 1) +
    annotate("text", x = mu*1.01, y = 75, 
             label = paste("Mean:", round(mu, 4)), 
             color = "red", hjust = 0) +
    annotate("text", x = mu*1.01, y = 75 * 0.90, 
             label = paste("Sd:", round(s_d, 4)), 
             color = "red", hjust = 0)+
    ggtitle(sprintf("Moran's I=%s (seed=%s)",moran2sim,seed)) +
    xlab("Global Moran's I") +
    ylab('Count')+
    ylim(c(0,100))+
    theme_minimal()
  plist[[paste0(moran2sim,seed)]] = p
  }
}
grid.arrange(grobs=plist,ncol=3)
